fixed a bug regarding a roundtrip exporting (where side X exports an object to the other side Y, and Y re-exports that back to X.) When this happens to classloaders (that is, when the master exports its classloader to a remote machine, which re-exports this remote classloader to the master to make a callback), we end up creating a RemoteClassLoader on the master to load a duplicate copy. A duplicate copy happens when we try to load a class from plugins, because ImportedClassLoaderTable creates new RemoteClassLoader with the 'getClass().getClassLoader()' as the parent, which doesn't see the plugin classes. To fix this problem, RemoteClassLoader is modified to detect the situation where a round-trip re-exporting is about to happen. Upon detecting this, it will arrange things in such a way that the other side will get the original ClassLoader instance back, instead of doubly-proxied RemoteClassLoader. This fixes the problem discussed in http://www.nabble.com/Help-Kohsuke%21-m2-project-type-and-cobertura-tf4829718.html and http://www.nabble.com/MavenReporter-throws-Serialization-Exception-for-ProjectActions-when-writing-to-build.xml-tf4784290.html#a13687067 git-svn-id: https://hudson.dev.java.net/svn/hudson/trunk/hudson/main@5997 71c3de6d-444a-0410-be80-ed276b4c234a

keep the master build around while all the configurations are built. This is to avoid next MatrixBuild to start executing while configurations of the previous MatrixBuild is still building. If we don't do this and new MatrixBuild gets scheduled frequently, then it becomes impossible for MatrixBuild to have all its MatrixConfigurations built. Instead, we'd get every MatrixBuild to contain a subset of MatrixRuns, and never get the whole picture. git-svn-id: https://hudson.dev.java.net/svn/hudson/trunk/hudson/main@3577 71c3de6d-444a-0410-be80-ed276b4c234a

I thought the use of the 'close' field and synchronization is enough to guard against this condition, but apparently it's not. I added one more 'closing' field, which seems to fix the problem. The reason seams to be that our SVN users have the following structure: WINDOWSDOMAIN\UserName (with back slash). Hudson knows the user who checked in (e.g.: WINDOWSDOMAIN\UserName).Hudson tries to create a folder with this name in HUDSON_HOME/users/, and that is not possible with the back slash on Windows!
